.TH PROXIMO 1 "July 2026" "proximo 0.22.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
proximo \- Model Context Protocol server for Proxmox VE
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B proximo
.br
.B proximo doctor
[\fB\-\-target\fR \fINAME\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B proximo
is a Model Context Protocol (MCP) server that exposes Proxmox VE management
\(em and, optionally, Proxmox Backup Server, Proxmox Mail Gateway, and
Proxmox Datacenter Manager \(em as a tool surface for MCP clients (AI
agents, IDE integrations, and similar). It manages Proxmox over its REST
API using a scoped API token, plus an opt-in in-container execution edge
(\fBssh\fR followed by \fBpct exec\fR) that is off by default.
.PP
.B proximo
speaks MCP over standard input/output only. It is meant to be launched
on demand by an MCP client (for example, entered into that client's MCP
server configuration), not started as an always-on network daemon and not
run interactively at a shell prompt. With no arguments it starts the
stdio server and blocks, reading MCP protocol frames from stdin and
writing responses to stdout, until the client closes the stream.
.PP
Every mutating tool call is governed by a trust spine that is on by
default and cannot be disabled by configuration:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
.B PLAN
\(em a dry-run preview is generated before any mutating call is allowed
to take effect; nothing mutates without a preceding plan.
.IP \(bu 2
.B PROVE
\(em a hash-chained, tamper-evident audit ledger records every plan and
every confirmed action (HMAC-keyed by default).
.IP \(bu 2
.B UNDO
\(em snapshot, config-revert, or rollback primitives are used wherever
the targeted Proxmox plane supports them.
.IP \(bu 2
.B DIAGNOSE
\(em a read-only evidence battery, always available, independent of the
other three.
.RE
.PP
A further set of controls (per-plan CONSENT, a CONTAIN kill-switch, an
arm-lease TTL, target SCOPE/provenance checks, a FORBID+RATE ENVELOPE, and
content TAINT tracking) is entirely opt-in: each is inert until its
corresponding \fBPROXIMO_*\fR environment variable is set. Risk ratings
reported by proximo's tools are an advisory heuristic, not a sandbox.
.SH THE DOCTOR SUBCOMMAND
.TP
.B proximo doctor \fR[\fB\-\-target\fR \fINAME\fR]
Read-only preflight check. Verifies that the configured Proxmox API is
reachable and reports what the configured token CAN and CANNOT do;
each capability gap lists the missing privilege and a role that would
grant it. Never starts the MCP server. Prints a single JSON report to
standard output and exits 0 whether or not the target turned out to be
reachable \(em an unreachable host or an insufficiently-privileged token
is a reported finding, not a failure of \fBdoctor\fR itself. A hard
configuration problem (for example a required \fBPROXIMO_*\fR variable
that is missing) is instead printed as a short message on standard error
and exits with status 1.
.IP
Run \fBproximo doctor\fR once right after install, and again after any
configuration change, before wiring \fBproximo\fR into an MCP client.
.TP
.BI \-\-target\ NAME
Probe a named remote from the \fBPROXIMO_TARGETS\fR registry (see
\fBENVIRONMENT\fR below) instead of the default single-target
\fBPROXIMO_*\fR environment.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
Proximo is configured entirely through environment variables; there is no
separate configuration-file syntax of its own (see \fBFILES\fR below for
the optional \fIproximo.env\fR loader). This section lists only the
handful of variables needed to get started \(em it is deliberately not a
full reference; see \fBFILES\fR for where the complete list lives.
.PP
Required for the default single-target setup:
.TP
.B PROXIMO_API_BASE_URL
Proxmox VE API base URL, e.g. \fIhttps://pve.example.lan:8006/api2/json\fR.
.TP
.B PROXIMO_NODE
Default Proxmox node name.
.TP
.B PROXIMO_TOKEN_PATH
Path to a file containing exactly \fIUSER@REALM!TOKENID=SECRET\fR. The
file is read at call time, not held in memory at rest; never pass the
token itself as an inline environment value.
.PP
Notable safety toggles, both off by default:
.TP
.B PROXIMO_ENABLE_EXEC
Turns on the in-container exec edge (\fBssh\fR \(-> \fBpct exec\fR), gated
by the fail-closed \fBPROXIMO_CT_ALLOWLIST\fR.
.TP
.B PROXIMO_ENABLE_AGENT
Turns on the in-guest QEMU guest-agent edge, gated by the fail-closed
\fBPROXIMO_AGENT_ALLOWLIST\fR.
.PP
The complete \fBPROXIMO_*\fR reference \(em every variable, every plane
(PVE/PBS/PMG/PDM), the opt-in trust-spine extensions, and multi-target
registries \(em is documented in \fI/usr/share/doc/proximo/proximo.env.example\fR
and in the upstream README (see \fBSEE ALSO\fR).
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.config/proximo/proximo.env
Optional. Sourced once at process start; fills only \fBPROXIMO_*\fR names
that are not already set in the real environment (real/inline environment
always wins). Override the path with \fBPROXIMO_ENV_FILE\fR. This exists
so an MCP client's inline \fIenv\fR block and a file-based configuration
behave the same way.
.TP
.I /usr/share/doc/proximo/proximo.env.example
The complete, annotated \fBPROXIMO_*\fR environment variable reference,
shipped with this package.
.TP
.I /opt/venvs/proximo/
The self-contained Python virtual environment bundling proximo and its
runtime dependencies (\fImcp\fR, \fIhttpx\fR). \fI/usr/bin/proximo\fR is a
symlink into it. Not meant to be activated or modified directly.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Normal exit: the MCP client closed the stdio stream, or \fBdoctor\fR
completed its preflight report (regardless of whether the target was
reachable or fully privileged).
.TP
.B 1
Configuration error: an unknown \fBPROXIMO_SURFACES\fR entry was given, a
required \fBPROXIMO_*\fR variable was missing when \fBdoctor\fR tried to
build its report, or another preflight error occurred. A short message is
printed to standard error in place of a traceback.
.SH SEE ALSO
Full documentation, the complete environment variable reference, and the
trust-spine design: \fIhttps://github.com/john-broadway/proximo\fR
.PP
.I /usr/share/doc/proximo/README.Debian
